==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic (cognate with Old Frisian ''dūra'' (Frisian [[doare]]), Old High German [[giturran]], Old Saxon [[gidurran]]), from an Indo-European base which also gave Greek [[θαρσειν]] ‘be bold’.

===Pronunciation===
{{IPA|/'dʊr:an/}}

===Verb===
'''durran''' (preterite-present verb: '''dearr''' ‘he dares’; '''dearst''' ‘you dare’; '''durron''' ‘they dare’; '''dorste''' ‘he dared’)
# to [[dare]]

